{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480855"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"118"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/118"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.06,0.17,0.18,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"118"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77118"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/118"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"118"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62625"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"3535"},{"type":"tags","id":"3764"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44915"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77118"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of increasing right leg pain and headaches. His right leg pain worsens on weight bearing and is not relieved by rest or paracetamol. His headache is constant and dull, worsening when wearing a hat. He has a family history of osteoarthritis but no significant medical history himself. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is bowing of the anterior right tibia, and his range of motion is limited by pain. Blood tests show alkaline phosphatase 300 U/L (35-110) with normal calcium, phosphate, and other biochemistry.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is most likely to develop in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Impaired hearing","Pancytopenia","Bone sequestrum","Osteosarcoma","Renal insufficiency"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features characteristic of Paget\u0027s disease of bone, including localised bone pain, tibial bowing, and isolated elevation of alkaline phosphatase. The headache suggests skull involvement, which occurs in approximately 40% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired hearing\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely complication, occurring in up to 61% of patients with skull involvement. This results from compression of the vestibulocochlear nerve due to bone expansion and deformity of the skull base.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancytopenia\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical complication of Paget\u0027s disease. While the condition can affect bone marrow architecture, it does not typically interfere with haematopoiesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone sequestrum\u003C/strong\u003E formation (dead bone tissue separated from healthy bone) is more commonly associated with osteomyelitis rather than Paget\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare complication of Paget\u0027s disease, occurring in less than 1% of cases. While it should be considered in cases of sudden pain change, it is not the most likely complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical complication of Paget\u0027s disease. While the condition can cause elevated calcium levels in some cases, significant kidney dysfunction is rare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther common complications of Paget\u0027s disease include pathological fractures, osteoarthritis (occurring in 73% of cases), spinal stenosis, and high-output cardiac failure due to increased vascularity of affected bones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paget\u0027s disease of bone commonly affects the skull, pelvis, spine, femur and tibia.","Hearing impairment occurs in up to 61% of patients with skull involvement in Paget\u0027s disease.","Elevated alkaline phosphatase with normal calcium is characteristic of Paget\u0027s disease."],"references":["Shaker JL. Paget\u0027s Disease of Bone: A Review of Epidemiology, Pathophysiology and Management.\u00a0Ther Adv Musculoskelet Dis. 2009;1(2):107-125. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3383486/ DOI:10.1177/1759720X09351779","Stephen PT, Robert L, Julie W, Babitha M, Roger F. Adult Paget\u2019s disease of bone: a review. British Society for Rheumatology. 2017 Dec;56(12):2050-2059 Available at: https://academic.oup.com/rheumatology/article/56/12/2050/3003298"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62625"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"118"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62625"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T09:32:16+10:30","up